        </div>
      </div>

      <section class="section">
        <h2 class="section-title">In-Depth Performance</h2>

        <div class="content-block">
          <h3>Image Quality & Sensor Performance</h3>
          <p>
            The 33-megapixel back-illuminated Exmor R sensor represents a significant upgrade from the 24MP A7 III. Resolution is sufficient for large prints.and significant cropping while maintaining excellent high-ISO performance. Dynamic range measures approximately 14 stops at base ISO, providing substantial latitude for shadow recovery and exposure adjustments.
          </p>
          <p>
            High-ISO performance is impressive‚ÄîISO 6400 produces clean, professional-grade images with excellent color retention. The BIONZ XR processor enables faster processing and improved noise reduction algorithms. Sony's color science has matured significantly, with natural, pleasing skin tones straight out of camera. The 14-bit RAW files are remarkably pliable in post-processing.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="content-block">
          <h3>Autofocus System</h3>
          <p>
            The A7 IV features 759 phase-detection AF points covering 94% of the frame. Real-time Eye AF recognizes humans, animals, and birds with exceptional accuracy. Subject tracking is tenacious, maintaining focus on moving subjects through complex backgrounds with success rates exceeding 95%.
          </p>
          <p>
            Low-light AF performance is excellent, working reliably down to -4 EV with fast lenses. The tracking algorithm is predictive, anticipating subject movement for improved hit rates. While not quite as advanced as the latest AI-based systems (A7C II, A9 III), the A7 IV's autofocus remains highly reliable for professional work including weddings, events, and portraits.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="content-block">
          <h3>Video Capabilities</h3>
          <p>
            Video specifications are competitive for a hybrid camera. 4K 60p is available with a 1.5x crop (Super35), while 4K 30p uses the full sensor width with excellent oversampling from 7K. S-Log3 and S-Cinetone profiles provide flexibility for color grading. 10-bit 4:2:2 internal recording ensures maximum quality.
          </p>
          <p>
            Rolling shutter is noticeable in full-frame 4K modes due to the non-stacked sensor‚Äîthis is the primary video limitation. Focus breathing compensation works with supported Sony lenses, eliminating the "breathing" effect during focus pulls. Heat management allows approximately 45-60 minutes of continuous 4K 60p recording with latest firmware.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="content-block">
          <h3>Professional Ergonomics & Build</h3>
          <p>
            The A7 IV is designed for professional reliability. The deep grip accommodates all-day shooting with heavy lenses. Dual card slots (CFexpress Type A + SD UHS-II) provide redundancy and flexibility. The full-size HDMI port is far more reliable than micro-HDMI for video work.
          </p>
          <p>
            The 3.69M-dot OLED EVF (0.78x magnification) is bright and detailed. The 3.0" vari-angle touchscreen enables comfortable composition at any angle. Build quality is robust with magnesium alloy construction and comprehensive weather sealing. Battery life provides approximately 580 shots per charge (NP-FZ100), with real-world performance often exceeding 800 shots.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <h2>Ideal Lenses</h2>
        <div class="grid">
          <article class="card card-plain">
            <h3>Sony 24-70mm f/2.8 GM II</h3>
            <p>Ultimate pro zoom, surprisingly light.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="card card-plain">
            <h3>Sony 85mm f/1.8</h3>
            <p>Affordable, sharp, fast portrait lens.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="card card-plain">
            <h3>Sigma 24-70mm f/2.8 DG DN</h3>
            <p>Great value alternative to the GM.</p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section" id="affiliate">
        <h2>Affiliate Disclosure</h2>
        <p class="section-sub">
          We buy our own gear or rent it. No manufacturers paid for this review.
          We earn a commission if you use our links, which keeps this site
          ad-free.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-container">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>
              <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
                <span class="faq-icon"></span>
                Should I choose the A7 IV or A7C II?
              </button>
            </h3>
            <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
              <p>
                Choose the A7 IV if you need the professional grip, dual card
                slots, and better button layout for fast-paced work. The A7C II
                is better if portability is paramount and you're primarily
                shooting travel or everyday content. Both share the same sensor
                and AF system, so image quality is identical.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>
              <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
                <span class="faq-icon"></span>
                Is the Sony A7 IV good for sports photography?
              </button>
            </h3>
            <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
              <p>
                It's capable for casual sports with 10fps shooting and excellent
                Eye AF, but it's not ideal for professional sports. The buffer
                clears slower than dedicated sports cameras, and the mechanical
                shutter can cause blackout. For serious sports work, consider
                the A9 III or A1 which offer 30fps+ with no blackout.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>
              <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
                <span class="faq-icon"></span>
                Does the A7 IV overheat during video recording?
              </button>
            </h3>
            <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
              <p>
                With the latest firmware, overheating is well-managed. You can
                shoot 4K60 for 45-60 minutes continuously in most conditions.
                The S35 crop mode runs cooler than full-frame. In hot weather
                (30¬∞C+), enable "High" temperature mode in settings to extend
                recording time.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>
              <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
                <span class="faq-icon"></span>
                What memory cards should I use with the A7 IV?
              </button>
            </h3>
            <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
              <p>
                For 4K60 10-bit, use UHS-II V60 cards minimum (like Sony SF-G or
                ProGrade Digital). For 4K30, V30 cards work fine. The CFexpress
                Type A slot is overkill unless you shoot 4K120 or need faster
                buffer clearing for bursts. Save money and stick with UHS-II
                cards.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>
              <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
                <span class="faq-icon"></span>
                Can the A7 IV use older E-mount lenses?
              </button>
            </h3>
            <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
              <p>
                Yes, all Sony E-mount lenses work perfectly, including older FE
                and even APS-C lenses (which auto-crop). Third-party lenses from
                Sigma, Tamron, and Samyang also work well, though some older
                models may need firmware updates for full compatibility with the
                advanced AF system.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

